	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Actually guys, you're wrong and I'll tell you why.  Verant needed to do this to stay competitive.  Around Christmas time, a lot of people are going to be getting into MMRPG's for the first time, or will be looking to pick a new one.  They're bumping up the requirements on the new expansion to stay competitive.  Believe it or not, graphics are a huge selling point to a game.<BR>
<BR>
And, the requirements on Luclin aren't any higher than the that of other games that are going to be released around that time.<BR>
<BR>
Verant was faced with the decision to continue to build onto the existing world and stay competitive, or scrape it for EQ2.  When you think about it, if your system doesn't meet the requirements, you should kinda be grateful that the did the first instead of second or else you'd be stuck with a game with no future expansion, upgrade, or support in sight.  Heck, might even have pulled down the old servers eventually.<BR>
<BR>
I can feel with all of you who have older systems, but you can't expect a company to continue to publish expansion packs for a game nearly 3 years after release with the orriginal system requirements.  That's like getting mad at Squaresoft that Final Fantasy X, XI, etc. won't come out on the PSX.<BR>
<BR>
Luclin is an expansion, which means it expands on what is already there.  You don't HAVE to buy it...you can still play everything else.  But don't get mad at Verant for staying competitive...<BR>
<BR>
One more note...by the time the game comes out, those requirements won't be high by any standards.  I feel for you guys...I know how it feels to be tight on money.  All I can say is to save a little every month and read up on how to build or upgrade a computer...parts are cheap these days, and most people could upgrade well beyond those requirements for $150-200.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
